# MLB Strikeout Pipeline — environment configuration
# Copy to `.env` for local use, or set these as variables on each Railway service.
# Everything here is OPTIONAL: with nothing set, the pipeline runs against the
# local filesystem (data/storage/) and works with zero credentials.

# ── Object storage (snapshot + feature persistence) ──────────────────────────
# The snapshot/features must outlive Railway's ephemeral filesystem so the web
# dyno can read what the cron service wrote. Point both services at the same
# bucket. Leave STORAGE_BACKEND unset (or "local") to use the local-FS stub.
#
# STORAGE_BACKEND=s3
#
# Cloudflare R2 example:
#   S3_BUCKET=mlb-strikeouts
#   S3_ENDPOINT_URL=https://<accountid>.r2.cloudflarestorage.com
#   S3_ACCESS_KEY=<r2-access-key-id>
#   S3_SECRET_KEY=<r2-secret-access-key>
#   S3_REGION=auto
#
# AWS S3 example (omit S3_ENDPOINT_URL to use the default endpoint):
#   S3_BUCKET=mlb-strikeouts
#   S3_ACCESS_KEY=<aws-access-key-id>
#   S3_SECRET_KEY=<aws-secret-access-key>
#   S3_REGION=us-east-1

# ── Railway deployment layout ────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Two services from this one repo (see Procfile):
#
#   1. web  — start command: uvicorn api:app --host 0.0.0.0 --port $PORT
#             Always-on. Serves pre-computed predictions. Never scrapes.
#
#   2. cron — start command: python cron_daily.py
#             A Railway *Cron Job* service. Set its Cron Schedule to run once
#             each morning before lineups lock, e.g.:
#                 0 13 * * *        # 13:00 UTC ≈ 08:00 ET
#             It builds the Statcast snapshot, runs inference for today, and
#             exits. Lineup-confirm re-runs are handled by POST /admin/refresh
#             on the web service.
#
# Both services should share the STORAGE_* variables above so the cron service's
# writes are visible to the web service.
